A  digha supermarket can significantly contribute to air pollution through various factors. The operation of delivery trucks and customer vehicles adds to greenhouse gas emissions and particulate matter. Inside, refrigeration systems and other equipment may release refrigerants that harm the ozone layer. Additionally, the energy used for lighting and heating often comes from fossil fuels, further increasing the carbon footprint. Waste management practices, if not properly managed, can also lead to odors and emissions. Overall, while supermarkets provide essential services, their environmental impact necessitates sustainable practices to mitigate air pollution.

These substances can degrade air quality and pose health risks, leading to respiratory issues and exacerbating existing health conditions.
